    {
      "content": "How to use multiple clients with a single mobile service backend | Microsoft Azure",
      "pos": [
        27,
        109
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Learn how to use a single mobile service back-end from multiple client apps that target different mobile platforms, including Windows Store and Windows Phone.",
      "pos": [
        128,
        286
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Supporting multiple device platforms from a single mobile service",
      "pos": [
        619,
        684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One of the major benefits of using Azure Mobile Services in your mobile app development is the ability to use a single backend service that supports your app on multiple client platforms.",
      "pos": [
        686,
        873
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services provides native client libraries for all major device platforms, which makes it easier to develop apps using a single backend service and by using cross-platform developer tools.",
      "pos": [
        874,
        1068
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This topic discusses considerations for getting your app running on multiple client platforms while using a single mobile service backend.",
      "pos": [
        1069,
        1207
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1211,
        1261
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a id=\"push\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Cross-platform push notifications"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services uses Azure Notification Hubs for sending push notifications to your client apps on all major device platforms.",
      "pos": [
        1263,
        1389
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Notification Hubs provide a consistent and unified infrastructure for creating and managing device registrations and for sending cross-platform push notifications.",
      "pos": [
        1390,
        1553
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Notification Hubs supports sending push notifications by using the following platform-specific notification services:",
      "pos": [
        1554,
        1671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Apple Push Notification Service (APNS) for iOS apps",
      "pos": [
        1675,
        1726
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Google Cloud Messaging (GCM) service for Android apps",
      "pos": [
        1729,
        1782
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Windows Notification Service (WNS) for Windows Store, Windows Phone 8.1 Store, and universal Windows apps",
      "pos": [
        1785,
        1890
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Push Notification Service (MPNS) for Windows Phone Silverlight apps",
      "pos": [
        1893,
        1970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>Notification Hubs does not currently support using WNS to send push notifications to Windows Phone Silverlight 8.1 apps.",
      "pos": [
        1973,
        2105
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must use MPNS to send notifications to Silverlight and Windows Phone 8.0 and 7.0 apps.",
      "pos": [
        2106,
        2196
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Azure Notification Hubs].",
      "pos": [
        2198,
        2250
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Client registrations are created by using the register function in the platform-specific Mobile Services client library or by using the Mobile Services REST APIs.",
      "pos": [
        2252,
        2414
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Notification Hubs supports two kinds of device registrations:",
      "pos": [
        2415,
        2476
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Native registration<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>",
      "pos": [
        2480,
        2503
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Native registrations are tailored to the platform-specific push notification service.",
      "pos": [
        2508,
        2593
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When sending notifications to devices registered using native registrations, you must call platform-specific APIs in your mobile service.",
      "pos": [
        2594,
        2731
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To send a notification to devices on multiple platforms requires multiple platform-specific calls.",
      "pos": [
        2732,
        2830
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Template registration<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>",
      "pos": [
        2834,
        2859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Notification Hubs also supports platform-specific template registrations.",
      "pos": [
        2864,
        2937
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By using template registrations, you can use a single API call to send a notification to your app running on any registered platform.",
      "pos": [
        2938,
        3071
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Send cross-platform notifications to users].",
      "pos": [
        3072,
        3143
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>An error occurs when trying to send a message to a native device platform for which no device registrations exists.",
      "pos": [
        3146,
        3273
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This error does not occur when sending template notifications.",
      "pos": [
        3274,
        3336
      ]
    },
