    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a id=\"xplat-app-dev\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Cross-platform app development",
      "pos": [
        9330,
        9386
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developing native mobile device apps for all of the major mobile device platforms requires you (or your organization) to have expertise in at least Objective-C, Java, and C# or JavaScript programming languages.",
      "pos": [
        9387,
        9597
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because of the expense of developing across these disparate platforms, some developers choose a fully web browser-based experience for their apps.",
      "pos": [
        9598,
        9744
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, such web-based experiences cannot access most of the native resources that provide the rich experience that users have come to expect on their mobile devices.",
      "pos": [
        9745,
        9912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cross-platform tools are available that provide a richer native experience on a mobile device, while still sharing a single code base, usually JavaScript.",
      "pos": [
        9916,
        10070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services makes it easy to create and manage a backend service for cross-platform app development platforms by providing quickstart tutorials for the following development platforms:",
      "pos": [
        10071,
        10259
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Appcelerator<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=509987)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        10263,
        10330
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Appcelerator lets you use JavaScript to develop a single app that is compiled to run  as native on all mobile device platforms.",
      "pos": [
        10335,
        10462
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This provides a rich user experience in UI, access to all native device resources, and native app performance.",
      "pos": [
        10463,
        10573
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the [Appcelerator tutorial][Appcelerator].",
      "pos": [
        10574,
        10642
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PhoneGap<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwLink/p/?LinkID=390707)</ept><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>/<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>Cordova<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept><ept id=\"p4\">](http://cordova.apache.org/)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        10646,
        10756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "PhoneGap (a distribution of the Apache Cordova project) is a free and open source framework that lets you use standardized web APIs, HTML and JavaScript to develop a single app that runs on Android, iOS and Windows devices.",
      "pos": [
        10761,
        10984
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "PhoneGap provides a web view based UI, but with a user experience enhanced by accessing native resources on the device, such as such as push notifications, the accelerometer, camera, storage, geolocation, and the in-app browser.",
      "pos": [
        10985,
        11213
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the [PhoneGap quickstart tutorial][PhoneGap].",
      "pos": [
        11214,
        11285
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Visual Studio now also enables you to build cross-platform Cordova apps by using the Multi-Device Hybrid Apps extension for Visual Studio, which is pre-release software.",
      "pos": [
        11291,
        11460
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Getting Started with Multi-Device Hybrid Apps Using HTML and JavaScript<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn771545.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11461,
        11610
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Sencha Touch<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=509988)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        11614,
        11681
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sencha Touch provides a set of controls, optimized for touch screens, that provide a like-native experience on a wide variety of mobile devices from a single HTML and JavaScript code base.",
      "pos": [
        11686,
        11874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sencha Touch can be used along with PhoneGap or Cordova libraries to provide users access to native device resources.",
      "pos": [
        11875,
        11992
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the [Sencha Touch quickstart tutorial][Sencha].",
      "pos": [
        11993,
        12066
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Xamarin<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwLink/p/?LinkID=330242)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        12070,
        12133
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Xamarin lets you create fully native apps for both iOS and Android devices, with fully native UI and access to all device resources.",
      "pos": [
        12138,
        12270
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Xamarin apps are coded in C# instead of Objective-C and Java.",
      "pos": [
        12271,
        12332
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This enables .NET developers to publish apps to iOS and Android and share code from Windows projects.",
      "pos": [
        12333,
        12434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Xamarin provides a fully native user experience on both iOS and Android devices from C# code.",
      "pos": [
        12435,
        12528
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This enables you to reuse some of your Mobile Services code from Windows apps on iOS and Android devices.",
      "pos": [
        12529,
        12634
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Xamarin development<ept id=\"p1\">](#xamarin)</ept> below.",
      "pos": [
        12635,
        12699
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can build Xamarin apps using either Xamarin Studio or Visual Studio 2013.",
      "pos": [
        12705,
        12782
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Cross-Platform Development in Visual Studio<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn771552.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12783,
        12904
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        12909,
        12981
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a id=\"shared-vs\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Sharing and reusing code in Visual Studio projects"
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Services includes a .NET client library, which is a .NET Framework Portable Class Library (PCL) that supports development on all Windows platforms.",
      "pos": [
        12983,
        13137
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [How to use a .NET client with Mobile Services].",
      "pos": [
        13138,
        13212
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This makes it easy to reuse the same Mobile Services code, such as for data access or authentication, in multiple C# projects.",
      "pos": [
        13213,
        13339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One general approach for sharing and reusing your C# code between projects is to implement the Model-View-ViewModel (MVVM) pattern and share assemblies across multiple platforms.",
      "pos": [
        13341,
        13519
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can implement the model and view model classes in a Portable Class Library project in Visual Studio, and then create views that are customized for different platforms.",
      "pos": [
        13520,
        13691
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The model code, common across platforms, may (as an example) retrieve the data from a source such as your mobile service in a platform-agnostic manner.",
      "pos": [
        13692,
        13843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The MSDN Library provides an <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/gg597391(v=vs.110)\"&gt;</ph>overview and example<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>, discussion of <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/gg597392(v=vs.110)\"&gt;</ph>API differences<ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>, an example of <ph id=\"ph5\">&lt;a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh563947(v=vs.110)\"&gt;</ph>using portable class libraries to implement the MVVM pattern<ph id=\"ph6\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>, additional <ph id=\"ph7\">&lt;a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windowsphone/develop/jj714086(v=vs.105).aspx\"&gt;</ph>prescriptive guidance<ph id=\"ph8\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>, and information about <ph id=\"ph9\">&lt;a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh871422(v=vs.110)\"&gt;</ph>managing resources<ph id=\"ph10\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph> in portable class library projects.",
      "pos": [
        13844,
        14473
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition to this general guidance, Visual Studio also provides specific facilities for reusing your mobile services code across multiple client app projects, which are discussed in the following sections.",
      "pos": [
        14475,
        14682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more general information about using Visual Studio 2013 to build cross-platform apps, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Cross-Platform Development in Visual Studio<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn771552.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        14683,
        14872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Universal Windows apps",
      "pos": [
        14880,
        14902
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 adds support for universal Windows app projects.",
      "pos": [
        14904,
        14980
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Universal apps are solutions that include both Windows Store 8.1 and Windows Phone Store 8.1 app projects along with a shared code project.",
      "pos": [
        14981,
        15120
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this kind of project, shared code is treated as if it is part of both the Windows Store and Windows Phone projects.",
      "pos": [
        15121,
        15239
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [Building universal Windows apps for all Windows devices].",
      "pos": [
        15240,
        15324
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Universal Windows apps can be written in both C#/XAML and JavaScript/HTML.",
      "pos": [
        15325,
        15399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, the Mobile Service quickstart tab in the [Azure Management portal] generates a universal Windows app version of the TodoList sample app to get you started.",
      "pos": [
        15401,
        15568
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can choose to download either a C#/XAML or a JavaScript/HTML version of the project.",
      "pos": [
        15569,
        15657
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Get started with Mobile Services<ept id=\"p1\">](../mobile-services-windows-store-get-started.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        15658,
        15768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>The C# version of the quickstart app project from the portal shares the MainPage.xaml.cs code-behind page but doesn't use a view model.",
      "pos": [
        15771,
        15918
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For an example of the TodoList app as a universal Windows app project in C# that uses MVVM, see [Universal Windows app project for Azure Mobile Services using MVVM].",
      "pos": [
        15919,
        16084
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        16089,
        16128
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a id=\"xamarin\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Xamarin development"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can leverage your Visual Studio and C# development experience, by using Xamarin and either Visual Studio or Xamarin Studio to develop apps for iOS and Android.",
      "pos": [
        16130,
        16293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Xamarin uses a cross-platform implementation of the .NET Framework that lets you use C# code to develop iOS and Android apps.",
      "pos": [
        16294,
        16419
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By using Xamarin, you can leverage existing code from your Windows projects that uses the Mobile Services .NET client library to access your mobile service.",
      "pos": [
        16420,
        16576
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Cross-Platform Development in Visual Studio<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn771552.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        16578,
        16699
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        16701,
        16897
      ],
      "content": "To get started building Xamarin apps that use Mobile Services, see the Xamarin quickstart tutorials (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>iOS<ept id=\"p1\">](mobile-services-ios-get-started.md)</ept> / <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Android<ept id=\"p2\">](mobile-services-android-get-started.md)</ept>)."
    },
    {
      "content": "Windows Store and Windows Phone Silverlight apps",
      "pos": [
        16904,
        16952
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Windows Phone 8.1, you can choose to use the previous Silverlight-based XAML for developing apps or use the Windows Runtime-based XAML, which enables the development of universal Windows apps.",
      "pos": [
        16954,
        17149
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about Windows Phone 8.1 Silverlight apps and Windows Phone Store 8.1 apps, see [What's next for Windows Phone 8 developers].",
      "pos": [
        17150,
        17295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Mobile Services .NET client library supports both Windows Phone Store 8.1 and Windows Phone Silverlight 8.1 apps.",
